like I play for
the New York Jets.

464
00:24:30,199 --> 00:24:31,562
How can we meet him?

465
00:24:32,731 --> 00:24:34,924
(STUTTERING) I don't know.
They have a class system.

466
00:24:34,998 --> 00:24:37,623
He's an aristocrat,
and, you know,
we're commoners.

467
00:24:37,798 --> 00:24:41,628
In fact, according to his
system, I think we're probably
classified as scum.

468
00:24:42,199 --> 00:24:44,562
This is our only chance.
He's all alone.

469
00:24:45,098 --> 00:24:46,563
Well, you're
a pretty girl.

470
00:24:46,631 --> 00:24:50,120
You know, I think you could
probably get this guy
to get interested in you.

471
00:24:50,199 --> 00:24:52,892
Don't be silly.
Particularly if he's got
a twisted mind.

472
00:24:55,398 --> 00:24:57,591
Look, I can't
just go up to him and say,
"Hi, how are you?"

473
00:24:57,665 --> 00:25:00,688
I mean,
what if he gets suspicious,
or, you know,

474
00:25:00,765 --> 00:25:03,163
if he gets put off, or...

475
00:25:03,264 --> 00:25:04,252
Drown.

476
00:25:04,998 --> 00:25:07,589
What?
Drown! Drown!
I'll go get... I'll go get...

477
00:25:07,665 --> 00:25:08,961
(SCOFFS)
Listen to me!

478
00:25:09,032 --> 00:25:10,224
I'll go get coffee.

479
00:25:10,298 --> 00:25:13,230
Get a cramp,
go in the water,
flounder around,

480
00:25:13,298 --> 00:25:14,491
you know. Yes!

481
00:25:15,032 --> 00:25:17,691
Go ahead, sweetheart.
That's a great idea.

482
00:25:17,765 --> 00:25:20,458
He'll be obliged
to save you that way.

483
00:25:20,531 --> 00:25:23,554
And if he doesn't...
lf, you know...
Then I'll notify your parents.

484
00:25:53,998 --> 00:25:54,986
SONDRA: (GASPS) Help!

485
00:25:55,998 --> 00:25:57,691
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

486
00:26:01,032 --> 00:26:02,020
Help!

487
00:26:05,032 --> 00:26:06,657
(SONDRA GASPING)

488
00:26:11,731 --> 00:26:13,890
(SONDRA COUGHING)
It's all right. Shh.

489
00:26:14,698 --> 00:26:16,857
It's okay.
There you go.

490
00:26:18,231 --> 00:26:19,822
Are you all right? Okay.

491
00:26:20,065 --> 00:26:21,053
I'm sorry.

492
00:26:21,198 --> 00:26:23,164
(COUGHING)
All right, here.
Here we are.

493
00:26:23,264 --> 00:26:25,196
Here we are. You all right?
Thank you.

494
00:26:25,498 --> 00:26:27,726
You okay?
Yes, thank you very much.

495
00:26:27,798 --> 00:26:29,559
Sorry.
It's my pleasure.
Here, let me help you out.

496
00:26:29,831 --> 00:26:30,819
(GRUNTS)

497
00:26:31,831 --> 00:26:33,456
I'm not a very good swimmer.

498
00:26:33,865 --> 00:26:35,194
(COUGHING)
It's all right.

499
00:26:35,298 --> 00:26:36,559
My leg cramped.

500
00:26:36,631 --> 00:26:37,688
Your leg?
Here, stretch it out.

501
00:26:37,765 --> 00:26:38,822
Oh.
That's it.

502
00:26:38,898 --> 00:26:40,158
Thank you.
No problem.

503
00:26:40,398 --> 00:26:42,830
Listen, you should always
do a little stretching
before you go in.

504
00:26:42,932 --> 00:26:45,454
You know,
that way you won't cramp.
Oh, thank you very much.

505
00:26:45,598 --> 00:26:48,064
I haven't been swimming
in so long.

506
00:26:48,731 --> 00:26:50,094
You're a new face.

507
00:26:50,431 --> 00:26:51,988
Have you
just become a member?

508
00:26:52,065 --> 00:26:54,462
Oh, no,
I'm a guest of the Fultons.

509
00:26:54,598 --> 00:26:56,791
Oh, right, Jack Fulton.
Yes, lovely chap.

510
00:26:57,198 --> 00:27:00,029
I'm Peter Lyman, by the way.
Hi, Son...

511
00:27:00,531 --> 00:27:01,519
Sond...

512
00:27:03,097 --> 00:27:04,222
Jade.

513
00:27:04,498 --> 00:27:05,691
Jade Spence.

514
00:27:05,965 --> 00:27:07,828
Jade Julliard Spence.

515
00:27:08,498 --> 00:27:10,794
That's a very pretty name.
Thank you.

516
00:27:10,932 --> 00:27:14,386
Yes, we're the Spences of...
Of Palm Beach.

517
00:27:14,865 --> 00:27:17,592
Oh, not the same Spences
who own the shipping line?

518
00:27:17,865 --> 00:27:19,194
No, no, no.

519
00:27:19,331 --> 00:27:23,229
My father's into
silver and gold

520
00:27:23,298 --> 00:27:25,230
and drilling.
Ah.

521
00:27:25,531 --> 00:27:26,588
For wells.

522
00:27:26,932 --> 00:27:28,955
What are you doing
in London?

523
00:27:29,464 --> 00:27:31,896
I'm here visiting friends
in Holland Park.

524
00:27:32,364 --> 00:27:34,193
Oh, good.
What do you do, Jade?

525
00:27:34,298 --> 00:27:37,059
Well, I am an actress.

526
00:27:37,131 --> 00:27:38,392
Oh, really?
Mmm-hmm.

527
00:27:38,665 --> 00:27:40,858
Yes, actually
I'm up for the part of Desiree

528
00:27:40,932 --> 00:27:42,955
in the new Mike Tinsley film.

529
00:27:43,032 --> 00:27:44,861
Oh, well, you're certainly
beautiful enough.

530
00:27:44,998 --> 00:27:46,588
(GIGGLING) Thank you.

531
00:27:46,731 --> 00:27:48,492
Look, Jade,

532
00:27:48,898 --> 00:27:49,955
if you're not busy,

533
00:27:50,031 --> 00:27:52,793
my father's giving
a garden party
at the estate on Sunday

534
00:27:52,865 --> 00:27:54,125
and I'd love you to come.

535
00:27:54,231 --> 00:27:57,322
I'd be very happy
to be your date
and show you around.

536
00:27:57,398 --> 00:28:00,262
The English countryside
is very lovely
this time of the year.

537
00:28:00,331 --> 00:28:02,490
Sounds fantastic.
Good.

538
00:28:02,598 --> 00:28:05,029
Do you mind
if I bring my father?

539
00:28:05,298 --> 00:28:06,594
Your father?

540
00:28:06,698 --> 00:28:08,789
Oh, look!
There he is right now.

541
00:28:09,264 --> 00:28:10,252
Ah.

542
00:28:10,431 --> 00:28:12,294
I was in the lounge.
I heard you drowning.

543
00:28:12,364 --> 00:28:15,558
I finished my tea and scones
and came immediately.

544
00:28:15,698 --> 00:28:17,357
SONDRA: Dad,
this is Peter Lyman,

545
00:28:17,431 --> 00:28:19,124
who was nice enough
to rescue me.

546
00:28:19,198 --> 00:28:20,186
Dad?

547
00:28:24,331 --> 00:28:26,058
Yes, of course, child!

548
00:28:26,131 --> 00:28:29,222
She cannot swim.
The girl cannot swim.

549
00:28:29,331 --> 00:28:32,491
Like a lead weight,
she sinks to the bottom
all the time.

550
00:28:32,631 --> 00:28:36,529
It's a family trait.
Lack of buoyancy, or...
Her siblings have it as well.

551
00:28:36,598 --> 00:28:39,462
Yes, well, listen,
pleasure to meet you,
Mr. Spence, right?

552
00:28:39,531 --> 00:28:40,554
Yes.

553
00:28:40,631 --> 00:28:43,028
Yes, and I'll see you
on Sunday at the estate.

554
00:28:43,097 --> 00:28:45,290
Oh, great.
Sunday? What's Sunday?
Not a fox hunt?

555
00:28:45,431 --> 00:28:48,420
(CHUCKLING)
No. No, Dad.
I'll explain it to you later.

556
00:28:48,565 --> 00:28:50,554
Listen, I'll leave
all the information
at the desk, all right?

557
00:28:50,631 --> 00:28:52,028
Hey, come, child.

558
00:28:54,264 --> 00:28:57,196
What kind of idiot are you?
Not a fox hunt?

559
00:28:57,298 --> 00:29:00,059
I'd like
to talk to these people
in their own terms.

560
00:29:00,264 --> 00:29:02,753
And, oh,
thanks for telling him
I'm your father.

561
00:29:02,898 --> 00:29:05,659
Oh, incidentally, he thinks
my name is Jade Spence,

562
00:29:05,731 --> 00:29:07,253
so that makes you
Mr. Spence.

563
00:29:07,331 --> 00:29:10,491
Wait a minute, I... This is
too tricky. I don't want to
go ahead with this.

564
00:29:10,665 --> 00:29:13,722
Why? What's wrong with you?
Your whole life is deception.
You're a magician.

565
00:29:13,831 --> 00:29:16,820
Yes, I'm a magician
and I want to stay a magician.
Can I have a Coke please?

566
00:29:16,898 --> 00:29:19,295
I don't want to get sued
or deported

567
00:29:19,364 --> 00:29:21,694
or arrested
for stalking somebody.

568
00:29:21,765 --> 00:29:23,890
This is a big guy
you're dealing with.

569
00:29:23,964 --> 00:29:26,760
This is a big story,
no kidding.
That's what Joe Strombel said.

570
00:29:26,831 --> 00:29:29,592
That's why he returned,
you know. This is
his last big scoop.

571
00:29:29,665 --> 00:29:30,892
Hey. What do I care
about Joe Strombel?

572
00:29:30,964 --> 00:29:34,658
Suddenly I'm taking direction
from a hunk of ectoplasm?

573
00:29:34,765 --> 00:29:36,697
This could be
very big for my career.

574
00:29:37,031 --> 00:29:40,759
Your career's fine.
You're on the college Bugle,
or whatever it is.

575
00:29:40,831 --> 00:29:42,421
You got years for scoops.

576
00:29:42,531 --> 00:29:44,121
You know what?
Forget you, all right.

577
00:29:44,198 --> 00:29:47,187
I'll do this on my own.
I don't need you.
Go back to your card tricks.

578
00:29:47,264 --> 00:29:49,025
I didn't say
I wouldn't help you.

579
00:29:49,097 --> 00:29:51,655
You know, I just...
It has to be done properly.

580
00:29:52,031 --> 00:29:54,054
You know, we gotta
put our heads together.

581
00:29:54,264 --> 00:29:57,128
If we put
our heads together,
you'll hear a hollow noise.

582
00:30:15,731 --> 00:30:18,060
Look at this place.
All it's missing is a moat.

583
00:30:23,064 --> 00:30:25,724
Ooh! Hey,
I could get used to this.

584
00:30:26,398 --> 00:30:27,625
Look at this.

585
00:30:29,598 --> 00:30:32,530
SONDRA: Oh, there he is.
Remember, Jade Spence.

586
00:30:32,731 --> 00:30:34,060
Jade...
Jade, who?

587
00:30:34,831 --> 00:30:36,660
(MUMBLING)

588
00:30:37,031 --> 00:30:38,429
Ah.
PETER: There you are.

589
00:30:38,498 --> 00:30:41,293
Hello.
How are you? Welcome,
Mr. Spence and Jade.

590
00:30:41,364 --> 00:30:42,523
Mr. Spence.

591
00:30:42,598 --> 00:30:46,030
You look stunning. Stunning.
Oh, thank you.
It's beautiful here.

592
00:30:46,097 --> 00:30:47,188
Thank you. Thank you. Yes.

593
00:30:47,264 --> 00:30:49,753
It's been in the family
for years. About 400 years.

594
00:30:49,864 --> 00:30:51,763
It's a little stuffy
for my taste, but...
Oh.

595
00:30:51,831 --> 00:30:54,126
She said,
"All that's missing
is a moat."

596
00:30:54,264 --> 00:30:57,230
Right.
(CHUCKLES) I love that.
I love the moat line.

597
00:30:57,298 --> 00:31:00,321
"All that's missing
is a moat." Beautiful.
Ah, this is my father.

598
00:31:00,598 --> 00:31:02,859
Father, Stephen Lyman,
this is... These are
my friends from America

599
00:31:02,931 --> 00:31:04,261
I was telling you about.
Oh, Lord Lyman.

600
00:31:04,364 --> 00:31:05,352
Jade Spence, Mr. Spence.

601
00:31:05,531 --> 00:31:06,962
How are you?
Hello.

602
00:31:07,031 --> 00:31:10,327
Curtsey, curtsey, curtsey,
curtsey, curtsey, curtsey,
I've never met a Lord before.

603
00:31:10,398 --> 00:31:11,489
How exciting!

604
00:31:11,565 --> 00:31:14,395
No, but there was
that Earl that we...
There was that Earl.

605
00:31:14,531 --> 00:31:16,190
I do hope
you're enjoying yourself.

606
00:31:16,264 --> 00:31:18,196
Peter, why don't you
show them around?

607
00:31:18,331 --> 00:31:19,797
Absolutely.
Would you like that?

608
00:31:19,931 --> 00:31:21,954
Oh, it...
Charmed, I'm sure.

609
00:31:22,097 --> 00:31:24,325
Should we hit
the buffet table first though?

610
00:31:24,398 --> 00:31:25,762
No, Dad.
Because the stuff
looks great.

611
00:31:25,830 --> 00:31:27,319
Remember,
we wanted to look around.

612
00:31:27,398 --> 00:31:29,227
(CHUCKLING)
Yes, of course, of course,
blessed offspring.

613
00:31:29,298 --> 00:31:31,594
Why don't we get a drink
and then we'll start inside?

614
00:31:31,765 --> 00:31:33,162
SONDRA: Oh, okay.
Come.

615
00:31:37,931 --> 00:31:40,762
Yes, I love this room here.
We often spend
evenings in here.

616
00:31:40,864 --> 00:31:42,353
The English countryside!

617
00:31:42,531 --> 00:31:45,691
It's elegant,
yet understated. I like that.

618
00:31:45,830 --> 00:31:47,296
You've done wonders
with the place.

619
00:31:47,498 --> 00:31:49,123
(CHUCKLES)
It brings to mind Trollope.

620
00:31:49,364 --> 00:31:51,159
Oh, do you enjoy
reading Trollope, too?

621
00:31:51,298 --> 00:31:53,787
No, no, not the author.
This was a girl I knew.

622
00:31:54,231 --> 00:31:57,026
Well, come. Let's go upstairs
and have a look at the view.

623
00:31:57,097 --> 00:31:58,085
Oh.

624
00:31:58,231 --> 00:32:00,890
Would you quit fooling around!
What's wrong with you?

625
00:32:00,997 --> 00:32:03,088
Try to pick up clues,
try to remember things.
I'm charming him.

626
00:32:03,164 --> 00:32:05,630
I remember. I got
a mnemonic system that I use.

627
00:32:05,731 --> 00:32:07,720
I use images, it's a trick.
Uh-huh, yeah.

628
00:32:07,830 --> 00:32:09,319
Say I want to remember
this ashtray.

629
00:32:09,398 --> 00:32:13,626
I think of, like, 50 ashtrays
dancing on a desert island
in hula skirts or something

630
00:32:13,864 --> 00:32:15,989
and then I remember.
I can call it
to mind whenever I...

631
00:32:16,064 --> 00:32:17,462
Where are you going?

632
00:32:17,830 --> 00:32:19,796
This is
one of the drawing rooms.

633
00:32:20,031 --> 00:32:22,190
Wow, this is
really beautiful, isn't it?

634
00:32:22,264 --> 00:32:24,560
Oh, here we have...
This is my great-grandfather.

635
00:32:24,665 --> 00:32:27,563
There's grandfather
and his wife, Lady Hayden.

636
00:32:27,631 --> 00:32:30,790
Reminds me of
the portrait of Aunt Hillary
in the library, no?

637
00:32:31,231 --> 00:32:35,527
Game woman, Hillary.
Suffragette, I believe.
Yeah. Diphtheria took her.

638
00:32:35,830 --> 00:32:38,456
Or perhaps it was elm blight.

639
00:32:39,097 --> 00:32:40,290
Come on, Dad.

640
00:32:41,198 --> 00:32:42,993
SONDRA: Oh,
this is just beautiful. Wow.

641
00:32:43,064 --> 00:32:45,587
Yes. I love the lake.
Do either of you fish?

642
00:32:45,665 --> 00:32:47,755
No, no, never have.
Oh, I'll have to teach you.

643
00:32:47,964 --> 00:32:50,260
I've taken some salmon,
you know. Organic.

644
00:32:50,464 --> 00:32:53,021
Yes, me, too.
I fly fish a little. But...

645
00:32:53,797 --> 00:32:55,388
So, Jade, do you
enjoy concerts?

646
00:32:55,464 --> 00:32:57,157
I'm very big
on the Philharmonic.

647
00:32:57,231 --> 00:32:58,629
We sponsor, in fact.

648
00:32:58,698 --> 00:33:00,822
I used to play the violin,
very, very badly.

649
00:33:01,064 --> 00:33:05,429
But I have a number of...
Well, actually quite a large
musical collection.

650
00:33:05,498 --> 00:33:07,191
Do you play an instrument,
either of you?

651
00:33:07,264 --> 00:33:08,560
Because we have
these lovely music gatherings.

652
00:33:08,631 --> 00:33:09,823
I do. Yes, I play the...

653
00:33:09,897 --> 00:33:10,885
(GRUNTS)

654
00:33:11,498 --> 00:33:14,430
Various classics,
you know, Noel Coward
and Shakespeare and...

655
00:33:14,964 --> 00:33:18,294
Right.
We gave her piano lessons
when she was a little girl,

656
00:33:18,364 --> 00:33:21,159
but her fingers
were just too stubby. So...

657
00:33:21,764 --> 00:33:23,492
Yes, what about you,
Mr. Spence?

658
00:33:23,931 --> 00:33:25,488
Well, I play the blues harp.

659
00:33:25,697 --> 00:33:27,925
It's a little metal thing
you put in your mouth

660
00:33:28,064 --> 00:33:30,292
and makes a twanging sound.
Very musical.
Yes, yes.

661
00:33:30,364 --> 00:33:33,592
Used to be called
the Jew's harp, but you know
how those people are.

662
00:33:33,665 --> 00:33:36,256
The slightest hint
of anti-Semitism
and they write letters.

663
00:33:36,464 --> 00:33:39,827
I would love it if you could
teach me how to fly fish.
That would be great.

664
00:33:39,897 --> 00:33:41,090
Oh, it would be my pleasure.

665
00:33:42,431 --> 00:33:45,659
Okay, I want you to
watch me very closely. Pay
very strict attention here.

666
00:33:45,797 --> 00:33:47,229
Now I want you
to take a card.

667
00:33:47,298 --> 00:33:48,786
Take any card you like.
You got it?

668
00:33:48,864 --> 00:33:50,558
Go ahead, sweetheart. Take it.
You got it?
Mmm-hmm.

669
00:33:50,631 --> 00:33:52,256
Now put it
in your pocketbook.
Put the card...

670
00:33:52,331 --> 00:33:53,524
She's gonna put the card
in her pocketbook.

671
00:33:53,598 --> 00:33:55,722
You got it? All right,
now tell everybody
what the card was.

672
00:33:56,164 --> 00:33:57,653
It was the six of hearts.
Six of hearts.

673
00:33:57,797 --> 00:33:58,785
Can I ask you a question?

674
00:33:58,864 --> 00:34:00,887
Was it
this six of hearts?

675
00:34:01,231 --> 00:34:02,424
But I just put that
in my bag.

676
00:34:02,498 --> 00:34:04,725
Well, check your card.
Check your card.

677
00:34:05,431 --> 00:34:06,419
It's amazing!

678
00:34:07,264 --> 00:34:08,923
You're
a wonderful sport, Claire.

679
00:34:08,997 --> 00:34:10,724
I mean that sincerely.
God bless you.

680
00:34:10,797 --> 00:34:13,195
You're a very sweet woman,
and this has been
a great group.

681
00:34:13,298 --> 00:34:16,458
From the bottom of my heart,
I say this with
all due respect.

682
00:34:16,697 --> 00:34:20,130
You're a wonderful... A credit
to your race and a
magnificent group of people.

683
00:34:20,198 --> 00:34:22,959
You know,
I must find out who
does the hedges here.

684
00:34:23,031 --> 00:34:24,724
Back home,
my topiary moose

685
00:34:24,797 --> 00:34:27,093
is starting
to look a little shabby
around the antlers.

686
00:34:27,164 --> 00:34:28,959
(LAUGHING) What do you do,
Mr. Spence?

687
00:34:29,031 --> 00:34:30,929
(STUTTERING) Me?
I'm in real estate.

688
00:34:31,264 --> 00:34:32,695
I'm sorry, I'm in oil!
I'm in oil.

689
00:34:32,764 --> 00:34:34,424
(STUTTERING) I was in
real estate,

690
00:34:34,498 --> 00:34:39,328
but, you know, land is
so difficult to come by now,
