01:23:58,461 --> 01:24:01,688
So, I'll be going.
I'll call you.
We'll have lunch.

1605
01:24:09,961 --> 01:24:14,326
Mr. Lyman, sir, Mr. Spence
has been here and he's
been into the music room.

1606
01:24:15,094 --> 01:24:16,390
What do you mean?

1607
01:24:16,661 --> 01:24:18,650
A most unusual
sequence of events.

1608
01:24:18,727 --> 01:24:20,989
Mr. Spence came by
looking for his
daughter's sweater.

1609
01:24:21,061 --> 01:24:22,550
Said she'd requested it.

1610
01:24:22,628 --> 01:24:24,855
Next thing I knew,
he was in the music room.

1611
01:24:25,361 --> 01:24:27,849
Sir, I think
he'd been drinking,
from his behavior.

1612
01:24:28,794 --> 01:24:31,090
Yes, yes.

1613
01:24:31,694 --> 01:24:34,286
Yes. Okay, Margaret,
thank you. Goodbye.

1614
01:24:35,428 --> 01:24:36,587
Is everything okay?

1615
01:24:36,661 --> 01:24:39,526
Yes.
Yes, it will be.

1616
01:25:54,627 --> 01:25:57,616
It's so nice
to be out here with you,
just away

1617
01:25:58,627 --> 01:26:01,059
from the rest of the world
and...
Hmm.

1618
01:26:01,128 --> 01:26:05,617
Yes, I often
come out here to read and,
well, and fish.

1619
01:26:05,694 --> 01:26:07,183
There's trout in the lake.

1620
01:26:16,094 --> 01:26:17,616
What are you thinking about?

1621
01:26:18,794 --> 01:26:20,385
You really want to know?
Yes.

1622
01:26:22,894 --> 01:26:25,553
Just how ironic life is,
and tragic.

1623
01:26:26,094 --> 01:26:27,355
Why?

1624
01:26:27,928 --> 01:26:30,519
Well, that I met you
by rescuing you from drowning

1625
01:26:31,328 --> 01:26:33,157
and found you
totally enchanting

1626
01:26:34,295 --> 01:26:37,749
and now we've come full cycle
and, alas, you're going
to have to drown.

1627
01:26:40,794 --> 01:26:41,885
What?

1628
01:26:42,328 --> 01:26:45,419
Oh, I imagine by now
Sidney's confirmed
that I killed Betty Gibson.

1629
01:26:45,494 --> 01:26:48,086
I mean, in my own defense,
there really was
no other way out.

1630
01:26:49,128 --> 01:26:51,424
At first I managed
to hide my identity from her,

1631
01:26:51,494 --> 01:26:53,653
but I saw her too many times
over the years

1632
01:26:54,928 --> 01:26:56,689
and she learned who I was,
and...

1633
01:26:57,228 --> 01:26:59,387
Well, it became
a constant demand for money

1634
01:26:59,461 --> 01:27:01,688
and I just
could not let that go on,
could I?

1635
01:27:02,727 --> 01:27:04,716
I mean, my whole life
and career

1636
01:27:04,794 --> 01:27:07,624
would be
just hostage to her
moods at all times.

1637
01:27:09,861 --> 01:27:12,089
So, I studied
the Tarot case,

1638
01:27:12,161 --> 01:27:14,490
I rehearsed my plan,
and, well, you know the rest.

1639
01:27:14,594 --> 01:27:16,492
If you do something to me,
Sidney's gonna find out!

1640
01:27:16,561 --> 01:27:17,686
He'll tell someone.

1641
01:27:17,761 --> 01:27:20,319
No, no, no.
You see, you will go
in a boating accident,

1642
01:27:20,395 --> 01:27:22,088
and Sidney will go
later tonight.

1643
01:27:22,527 --> 01:27:24,686
No one knows
of your relationship with him,

1644
01:27:25,128 --> 01:27:27,650
because, after all,
you're not actually father
and daughter, are you?

1645
01:27:28,395 --> 01:27:31,451
And no one will think twice
to investigate the death
of some obscure vaud...

1646
01:27:31,527 --> 01:27:32,754
Are you listening?

1647
01:27:33,061 --> 01:27:34,924
No one will think twice
to investigate the death

1648
01:27:34,994 --> 01:27:38,551
of some obscure vaudevillian
called Splendini, who is
really a stranger to me.

1649
01:27:39,295 --> 01:27:40,318
Help!

1650
01:27:40,395 --> 01:27:42,156
Help! Someone help me!

1651
01:27:49,094 --> 01:27:50,753
(CHUCKLES)

1652
01:27:51,094 --> 01:27:52,684
Yes, very quiet, isn't it?

1653
01:27:55,994 --> 01:27:58,017
This is the advantage
of a private lake.

1654
01:28:02,128 --> 01:28:04,094
Get off me!
Get off me!

1655
01:28:04,161 --> 01:28:05,149
(GRUNTS)

1656
01:28:05,994 --> 01:28:07,153
Get off me!
Come...

1657
01:28:36,394 --> 01:28:38,020
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1658
01:28:38,094 --> 01:28:39,082
(CRASHING)

1659
01:28:39,161 --> 01:28:40,286
(GLASS SHATTERING)

1660
01:28:46,928 --> 01:28:48,518
(PANTING)

1661
01:29:26,427 --> 01:29:28,053
(FEIGNING CRYING)
Yes, police.

1662
01:29:29,727 --> 01:29:33,125
Yes, this is Peter Lyman.
I need the police immediately.

1663
01:29:33,694 --> 01:29:35,683
At the Lyman estate.

1664
01:29:36,195 --> 01:29:39,786
There's been
a terrible boating accident.
A woman has drowned.

1665
01:29:39,861 --> 01:29:41,554
It's awful.
Please come right away.

1666
01:29:41,627 --> 01:29:43,116
Thank you. Thank you.

1667
01:29:46,494 --> 01:29:47,824
(SIGHS)

1668
01:29:50,028 --> 01:29:51,721
They think they know
where the body is.

1669
01:29:52,928 --> 01:29:54,393
I'm so sorry, sir.

1670
01:29:57,561 --> 01:29:59,289
When last I saw her,
she...

1671
01:30:03,028 --> 01:30:05,516
She just said she wanted
to go out there to
communicate with nature.

1672
01:30:07,061 --> 01:30:08,993
Just to think
she wanted some
peace and quiet and...

1673
01:30:09,427 --> 01:30:11,450
She wasn't depressed,
or anything like that,
was she, sir?

1674
01:30:11,527 --> 01:30:12,515
God, no. No.

1675
01:30:12,861 --> 01:30:15,054
I mean, unless she was
keeping it from me.

1676
01:30:15,327 --> 01:30:16,987
You heard no cries for help?

1677
01:30:17,061 --> 01:30:20,515
No! No,
I was listening to music
in here, damn it.

1678
01:30:21,228 --> 01:30:22,818
(SIGHS) It's just so ironic.

1679
01:30:22,894 --> 01:30:24,019
Because the way
I first met her

1680
01:30:24,094 --> 01:30:26,321
I rescued her
from drowning
in our club pool.

1681
01:30:26,394 --> 01:30:28,883
And she was a very,
very weak swimmer.

1682
01:30:29,627 --> 01:30:30,786
SONDRA: Hello?

1683
01:30:32,061 --> 01:30:34,549
I was faking it at the pool
to get your attention.

1684
01:30:34,928 --> 01:30:37,985
Actually, I used to be
captain of the Brooklyn
Community Swim Team.

1685
01:30:52,861 --> 01:30:54,417
Fascinating observation.

1686
01:30:54,594 --> 01:30:57,186
Lyman lost a cufflink
at the flat of a prostitute,

1687
01:30:57,260 --> 01:30:59,726
who was later killed
by the Tarot Card Killer.

1688
01:31:00,894 --> 01:31:04,417
Well, this upright chap
certainly enjoyed patronizing
some dodgy women.

1689
01:31:04,894 --> 01:31:08,451
Unfortunately
for Elizabeth Gibson,
she elected to blackmail him.

1690
01:31:09,827 --> 01:31:11,850
It's a beautifully
written story

1691
01:31:11,994 --> 01:31:15,858
and one of the best bits
of investigative journalism
in a long time.

1692
01:31:16,227 --> 01:31:18,194
And this paper
is proud to run it.

1693
01:31:18,260 --> 01:31:20,658
Oh, I have to
share the credit
with Joe Strombel.

1694
01:31:20,961 --> 01:31:21,984
An inspiration,

1695
01:31:22,061 --> 01:31:24,424
who taught me more
than I could ever
explain to anyone.

1696
01:31:24,494 --> 01:31:27,255
And to the late
Sidney Waterman.

1697
01:31:27,994 --> 01:31:29,119
Splendini.

1698
01:31:29,260 --> 01:31:31,988
A nice guy who helped out
with the investigation

1699
01:31:32,061 --> 01:31:34,686
and without whom
I never could have made it.

1700
01:31:36,094 --> 01:31:38,582
Sidney, wherever you are,

1701
01:31:39,727 --> 01:31:41,159
I'll never forget you.

1702
01:31:43,527 --> 01:31:44,390
WOMAN: How did you get here?

1703
01:31:44,794 --> 01:31:45,851
Me?

1704
01:31:45,961 --> 01:31:49,654
I couldn't get used to driving
on the goddamn wrong
side of the street!

1705
01:31:49,727 --> 01:31:51,716
(STUTTERING) You know,
I was driving up
to the country,

1706
01:31:51,794 --> 01:31:54,726
and in the United States,
I would have been a hero.
I would have saved her.

1707
01:31:54,794 --> 01:31:55,782
I would have...

1708
01:31:55,861 --> 01:31:58,383
But here, you know...
That's the one drawback
of living in London.

1709
01:31:58,460 --> 01:32:01,585
Granted, the theater's better,
there's many good
Indian restaurants.

1710
01:32:01,661 --> 01:32:02,854
Well, what did you do?

1711
01:32:02,961 --> 01:32:05,518
What do I do?
I'm Splendini. Magician.

1712
01:32:05,627 --> 01:32:06,615
(EXCLAIMS)

1713
01:32:06,727 --> 01:32:08,693
Would you like
to see something?
Oh, yes, please.

1714
01:32:08,761 --> 01:32:10,420
Do we have time
for a card trick?
Yes.

1715
01:32:10,494 --> 01:32:12,187
I believe we have eternity.

1716
01:32:12,260 --> 01:32:14,624
I'm going to show you
a little trick now.

1717
01:32:15,094 --> 01:32:17,855
I just want to say
from the bottom of my heart,
I mean this sincerely...

1718
01:32:18,527 --> 01:32:19,891
I say this
with all due respect.

1719
01:32:19,961 --> 01:32:22,620
You are a wonderful group and
a fantastic group of people.

1720
01:32:22,694 --> 01:32:25,353
I love you and I feel that
coming back from you.

1721
01:32:25,427 --> 01:32:29,757
And you may be deceased,
but you should not
be discouraged.

1722
01:32:29,827 --> 01:32:31,156
Because, you know...

1723
01:32:31,227 --> 01:32:33,785
Don't think of being dead
as a handicap.

1724
01:32:33,861 --> 01:32:35,986
You know,
when I was a child,
I stuttered.

1725
01:32:36,061 --> 01:32:38,458
But with stick-to-it-iveness
and perseverance,

1726
01:32:38,527 --> 01:32:40,493
you know, you can never tell
what could happen.

1727
01:32:40,561 --> 01:32:41,993
Now, I want you
to take a card, Alma.

1728
01:32:42,061 --> 01:32:43,321
Go ahead,
take any card you want.

1729
01:32:43,394 --> 01:32:45,088
Just pick it. Pick it.
Go ahead, sweetheart.

1730
01:32:45,160 --> 01:32:46,888
I love you, sweetheart.
That's fantastic.

